'''Yoshuku Performing Arts''' (予祝芸能) refers to forms of {{ill|Theatre of Japan|lt=traditional performing arts|ja|伝統芸能|en|12=draft}} viewed from a perspective of {{ill|faith|ja|信仰|12=draft}}, such as {{ill|Manzai|ja|萬歳|12=draft}} and {{ill|Hobby horse (toy)|lt=Harukoma|ja|春駒|fr|Cheval bâton|nl|Stokpaard|de|Steckenpferd|en|12=draft}}, which celebrate the New Year, or performances like {{ill|Ta-asobi|ja|田遊び|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ota|ja|御田|12=draft}} that simulate agricultural work to pray for a bountiful rice harvest.

These arts embody the act of preemptive celebration to pray for the realization of blessings, rooted in the belief and thought process associated with {{ill|Kotodama|ja|言霊|12=draft}}. Similar characteristics can be observed in the "Yashiki-bome" songs of {{ill|lion dance|ja|獅子舞|lt=lion dances|12=draft}} or {{ill|furyu dances|ja|風流踊り|12=draft}}. In contrast to Yoshuku Performing Arts, forms of art with a stronger focus on warding off disasters are sometimes referred to as {{ill|Josai Performing Arts|ja|除災芸能|12=draft}}.
